[[Major-general (United Kingdom)|Major General]] '''Simon Howe Brooks-Ward''', [[Royal Victorian Order|CVO]], [[OBE]], [[Territorial Decoration|TD]], [[Volunteer Reserves Service Medal|VR]], is a British event organiser and [[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|Army Reserve]] officer who served as [[Deputy Commander Field Army (United Kingdom)|Deputy Commander Field Army]] from October 2015 to January 2018. Through his company, The HPower Group, he is most well known for organising large-scale equestrian events worldwide.<ref>[http://hpowergroup.com/Simon_Brooks-Ward.html Biography ''Simon Brooks-Ward CVO OBE TD''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150815191026/http://hpowergroup.com/Simon_Brooks-Ward.html |date=15 August 2015 }} from HorsePower International website.</ref>

==Military career==
Brooks-Ward was commissioned into the [[Royal Yeomanry]] on 4 October 1987.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=51399|date=5 July 1988|page=7704 |supp=y }}</ref> He served in the [[Iraq War]] as the Commanding Officer of the Royal Yeomanry, the only Army Reserve unit to receive a battle honour during the conflict.<ref>[http://hpowergroup.com/Simon_Brooks-Ward.html Biography ''Simon Brooks-Ward CVO OBE TD''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150815191026/http://hpowergroup.com/Simon_Brooks-Ward.html |date=15 August 2015 }} from HorsePower International website.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lusher |first=Adam |date=20 April 2008 |title=Welcoming the troops at the Windsor Castle Royal Tattoo  |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1896158/Welcoming-the-troops-at-the-Windsor-Castle-Royal-Tattoo.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |location=London |accessdate=21 October 2015 }}</ref> In 2004 he was awarded the [[Territorial Decoration]], and in 2005 he was made an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (Military) for services in Iraq and to defence.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=57665|date=11 June 2005|page=5 |supp=y }}</ref> He was subsequently Colonel Yeomanry at Headquarters [[Royal Armoured Corps]] and Colonel TA Training at the [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]]. In January 2012 he was promoted to Brigadier and was appointed Assistant Divisional Commander of [[3rd (United Kingdom) Division]] in Bulford.<ref>[http://hpowergroup.com/Simon_Brooks-Ward.html Biography ''Simon Brooks-Ward CVO OBE TD''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150815191026/http://hpowergroup.com/Simon_Brooks-Ward.html |date=15 August 2015 }} from HorsePower International website.</ref> In October 2015 he was promoted to [[major-general]] and took over as [[Deputy Commander Field Army (United Kingdom)|Deputy Commander Field Army]], the most senior position in the Army Reserve.<ref>The Daily Telegraph (London), 2015, Senior army appointment, SECTION: FEATURES; Pg. 32, The Daily Telegraph (London), 24 August 2015.</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61398|supp=y|page=21527|date=2 November 2015}}</ref>

==Event organiser==
Brooks-Ward arranged his first major event at the age of 27, directing the [[Luciano Pavarotti]] horse show in Italy. He has subsequently become the director of the [[Olympia London International Horse Show]] and the [[Royal Windsor Horse Show]], as well as numerous other major equestrian events.<ref>[http://hpowergroup.com/Simon_Brooks-Ward.html Biography ''Simon Brooks-Ward CVO OBE TD''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150815191026/http://hpowergroup.com/Simon_Brooks-Ward.html |date=15 August 2015 }} from HorsePower International website.</ref>

In addition, Brooks-Ward was the Equestrian Edvisor at the [[2004 Summer Olympics opening ceremony]], the 2008 TA100 National Pageant, the Windsor Castle Royal Tattoo and the 2012 [[Diamond Jubilee Pageant]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Lusher |first=Adam |date=20 April 2008 |title=Welcoming the troops at the Windsor Castle Royal Tattoo  |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1896158/Welcoming-the-troops-at-the-Windsor-Castle-Royal-Tattoo.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |location=London |accessdate=21 October 2015 }}</ref> His involvement in many British state ceremonial occasions led to him being honoured as a [[Lieutenant of the Royal Victorian Order]] in 2002.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=56654|date=6 August 2002|page=2 |supp=y }}</ref> He was promoted to Commander in the same order in the [[2012 Diamond Jubilee Honours]] in recognition of his services during the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II]].<ref>[http://hpowergroup.com/Simon_Brooks-Ward.html Biography ''Simon Brooks-Ward CVO OBE TD''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150815191026/http://hpowergroup.com/Simon_Brooks-Ward.html |date=15 August 2015 }} from HorsePower International website.</ref>

He was involved in organising national celebrations for the Queen's 90th birthday in May 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rayner |first=Gordon |date=20 April 2008 |title=BBC misses out on showing Queen's 90th birthday celebrations after Jubilee criticism  |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/11608290/BBC-misses-out-on-showing-Queens-90th-birthday-celebrations-after-Jubilee-criticism.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |location=London |accessdate=15 May 2015 }}</ref>

